468. Lung. 2006 Jul-Aug;184(4):205-15. doi: 10.1007/s00408-005-2584-x.

Cardiopulmonary support in duchenne muscular dystrophy.

Finsterer J(1).

Author information:
(1)Krankenstalt Rudolfstiftung, Postfach 20, 1180 Vienna, Austria. 
duarte@aonmail.at

Duchenne muscular dystrophy (DMD) is an X-linked, rapidly progressive myopathy 
affecting the limb muscles, the respiratory muscles, the heart, the intestines, 
and the brain. Since about 90% of DMD patients die from muscular respiratory 
failure or cardiomyopathy, early and adequate therapy is essential. Ventilatory 
failure from muscle weakness requires mechanical support for ventilation and 
coughing as soon as there is symptomatic nocturnal hypoventilation. Today 
noninvasive positive-pressure ventilation (NIPPV) is the method of choice for 
supportive long-term mechanical ventilation in DMD. For assisted coughing, 
various methods are available, among which the mechanical in-exsufflator is the 
most widely used device. There is large nonrandomized clinical trial evidence 
that NIPPV improves quality of life and prolongs the lives of DMD patients if 
medical, social, economic, and ethical issues, raised by the availability of 
long-term NIPPV, are adequately addressed. Cardiac involvement in DMD manifests 
as impulse generation or impulse conduction abnormalities or cardiomyopathy. 
Cardiac abnormalities in DMD respond well to adequate therapy. Though DMD is 
ultimately a fatal disease, quality of life and life expectancy can be markedly 
improved if cardiopulmonary manifestations are adequately treated.

DOI: 10.1007/s00408-005-2584-x
PMID: 17006747 [Indexed for MEDLINE]


469. Health Econ. 2007 Apr;16(4):395-405. doi: 10.1002/hec.1170.

A comparison of patient and population values for health states in varicose 
veins patients.

Ratcliffe J(1), Brazier J, Palfreyman S, Michaels J.

Author information:
(1)Health Economics and Decision Science, University of Sheffield, Sheffield, 
UK. j.ratcliffe@sheffield.ac.uk

Cost utility analyses typically incorporate preferences based upon the mean 
values for health states generated from a sample of the general population. The 
main argument for using general population values rests upon the premise that in 
a publicly funded health care system the main objective of the health care 
system is a societal one, namely to maximise health subject to equity concerns. 
Alternatively, it can be argued that patients themselves should be asked to 
value their own health state given that they have first hand experience of the 
state being valued. This paper investigates the relationship between patient and 
general population values within the context of a randomised controlled trial to 
compare alternative treatments for varicose veins. It was found that patients' 
own health valuations tended to be higher than those of the general population 
sample. The results from this study have important implications for economic 
evaluation. The incremental QALY gain for patients receiving treatment for 
moderate varicose veins would be almost halved if patients' own values were used 
to estimate QALYs in contrast to the general population values. The results also 
suggest that the variant of elicitation technique may be more important than the 
source of those values in revealing discrepancies.

