479. J Med Ethics. 2006 Oct;32(10):571-4. doi: 10.1136/jme.2005.015420.

Killing people: what Kant could have said about suicide and euthanasia but did 
not.

Brassington I(1).

Author information:
(1)School of Law, University of Manchester, Manchester, UK. 
Iain.Brassington@manchester.ac.uk

Comment in
    J Med Ethics. 2008 Sep;34(9):655-7.

An agent who takes his own life acts in violation of the moral law, according to 
Kant; suicide, and, by extension, assisted suicide are therefore wrong. By a 
similar argument, and with a few important exceptions, killing is wrong; 
implicitly, then, voluntary euthanasia is also wrong. Kant's conclusions are 
uncompelling and his argument in these matters is undermined on considering 
other areas of his thought. Kant, in forbidding suicide and euthanasia, is 
conflating respect for persons and respect for people, and assuming that, in 
killing a person (either oneself or another), we are thereby undermining 
personhood. But an argument along these lines is faulty according to Kant's own 
standards. There is no reason why Kantians have to accept that self-killing and 
euthanasia are contrary to the moral law. Even if some Kantians adhere to this 
doctrine, others can reject it.

DOI: 10.1136/jme.2005.015420
PMCID: PMC2563317
PMID: 17012496 [Indexed for MEDLINE]

